  "prompt": "What is the present Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) of Nepal? What is the government doing to improve it?",
  "response": "As of 2021, Nepal's Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) is approximately 25 deaths per 1,000 live births, which represents a significant improvement from previous years. The Nepalese government has been implementing several strategies to reduce infant mortality:\n\n1. Government Initiatives:\n- Free maternal and child health services\n- Comprehensive immunization programs\n- Promoting institutional deliveries\n- Expanding healthcare infrastructure in rural areas\n- Providing nutrition support to mothers and children\n- Community-based health awareness programs\n\n2. Key Strategies:\n- Strengthening primary healthcare systems\n- Training skilled birth attendants\n- Implementing the Safe Motherhood Program\n- Ensuring access to basic healthcare services\n- Addressing malnutrition\n- Improving sanitation and hygiene\n\n3. Collaborative Efforts:\n- Working with international organizations like UNICEF\n- Partnering with NGOs for targeted healthcare interventions\n- Receiving technical and financial support from global health agencies\n\nThese efforts have contributed to a steady decline in infant mortality rates over the past decade, reflecting the government's commitment to improving child and maternal health.",
